# Day 11 - String Replacement

## Task
Replace all occurrences of the string `String` with `Sonar` in the XML file at `/root/nautilus.xml` on the jump host.

## Objective
Practice in-place text substitution using `sed` and verify changes using `grep`.

## Commands Used
```bash
# Count occurrences before substitution
sudo grep -c "String" /root/nautilus.xml

# Apply substitution and save to file
sudo sed -i 's/String/Sonar/g' /root/nautilus.xml

# Confirm original string is gone
sudo grep -c "String" /root/nautilus.xml

# Confirm replacement string exists
sudo grep -c "Sonar" /root/nautilus.xml
```

## What the Commands Do
- `grep -c` counts the number of matching lines in a file.
- `sed -i` edits the file in-place, saving changes directly.
- `s/String/Sonar/g` substitutes every occurrence of `String` with `Sonar` on each line.
- Without `-i`, `sed` only prints the result to the screen without modifying the file.
- Without `/g`, `sed` replaces only the first match per line.

## Verification
| Check | Result |
|---|---|
| `grep -c "String"` before | 66 occurrences |
| `grep -c "String"` after | 0 — all replaced |
| `grep -c "Sonar"` after | 66 — confirmed |

## What I Learned
- How `sed -i` performs in-place file editing.
- Why the `/g` flag is needed to replace all occurrences per line.
- How to verify substitutions using `grep -c` before and after.
- How filename typos cause "No such file or directory" errors.

## Personal Notes
This task reinforced the importance of a check-before, apply, verify-after workflow. It also showed that previewing `sed` output without `-i` first is a safe habit before committing changes to a file.
